<section>
  <title>Convergence of Sequences</title>

<definition>
  <notation><m>\lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} x_n=x_0</m></notation>
  <statement>A sequence <m>(x_n)</m> converges to a real number <m>x_0</m>if for every <m>\epsilon >0</m> there is an <m>N=N(\epsilon) \in \mathbb{N}</m> with the property that if <m>n &gt;N</m> then <m>|x_n-x_0| &lt; \epsilon</m>.</statement>
</definition>

<fact>
  <p>"As <m>n</m> gets bigger and bigger, <m>x_n</m> gets closer and closer to <m>x_0</m>."</p>
</fact>

<p>Last time, we proved:
  <ol>
    <li><m>\displaystyle \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \frac{1}{n}=0</m></li>
    <li><m>(started) \displaystyle \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty}  \frac{3n+1}{7n-4}=\frac{3}{7}</m></li>
  </ol>
</p>

<example><title>Convergent sequence: powers of 2</title>
<p workspace="10in">Prove that <m>\displaystyle \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \frac{1}{2^n}=0</m>.</p>

<p>SCRATCH WORK:
<md>
    <mrow>\left|\frac{1}{2^n}-0\right| \amp = \left|\frac{1}{2^n}\right|</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2^n} \text{ because values are all positive }</mrow>
  </md>.
We want to make this arbitrarily small.  That is, we want to show that for large <m>n</m>, this can be made smaller than <m>\epsilon</m>.  How big does <m>n</m> need to be?  We work to find out.  Specifically, we want to solve the inequality
<me>\frac{1}{2^n} &lt; \epsilon</me>.</p>

<p>Steps to solve for <m>n</m> follow:
  <md>
    <mrow>\frac{1}{2^n} &lt; \epsilon</mrow>
    <mrow>2^n &gt; \frac{1}{\epsilon}</mrow>
    <mrow>\log_2(2^n) &gt; \log_2(\frac{1}{\epsilon})</mrow>
    <mrow>n\log_2(2) &gt; -\log_2(\epsilon)</mrow>
    <mrow>n &gt; -\log_2(\epsilon)</mrow>
  </md>.
On the left side of the last inequality is the candidate for the <m>N</m> we seek, except that it isn't a natural number.  So we set <m>N=\lceil -\log_2(\epsilon) \rceil</m>.</p>
<p>We are now ready to prove the limit statement for the sequence <m>(2^{-n})</m>.</p>

<note>
  <p>Lots of proofs of convergence dispense with the requirement that our <m>N</m> be a natural number; the important aspect of <m>N</m> is that is ia a lower bound for the choices of <m>n</m> that make our expression <m>|x_n-x_0|</m>less than <m>\epsilon</m>.</p>
</note>


<proof>
  <p>Let <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> be given.  Choose <m>N=\lceil -\log_2(\epsilon) \rceil</m> and let <m>n &gt; N</m>.  For this choice of <m>n</m> we see that
  <md>
    <mrow>\left|\frac{1}{2^n}-0\right| \amp = \left|\frac{1}{2^n}\right|</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2^n}</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp &lt; \frac{1}{2^N} \text{ since }n&gt; N</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp &lt; \frac{1}{2^{-\log_2(\epsilon)}} \text{ since } N &gt; -\log_2(\epsilon)</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp &lt; \frac{1}{\epsilon^{-1}}</mrow>
    <mrow> \amp = \epsilon </mrow>
</md>
This shows that for <m>n>N</m>, we have <m>\left|\frac{1}{2^n}-0\right| &lt; \epsilon</m>, as desired.</p>
</proof>
</example>

</section>


<section><title>Convergence of Sequences</title>

<example><title>Convergent sequence (from last time)</title>
<p>Prove that <m>\displaystyle \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \frac{3n+1}{7n-4}=\frac{3}{7}</m>.</p>

<p workspace="9in">Last time, determined that <m>N=\lceil \frac{1}{7} \left( \frac{19}{7 \epsilon} +4 \right) \rceil</m>.</p>

