</section>

<section>
  <title>Convergence of Sequences</title>
  
<example><title>Convergent sequence</title>
<p workspace="10in">Prove that <md>\displaystyle \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \frac{4n^3+3n}{n^3-6}=4</md>.</p></example>

</section>

<section>
  <title>Divergence of Sequences</title>
  
<p>A sequence that does not converge is said to <term>diverge</term>.</p>

<definition>
  <statement>A sequence <m>(x_n)</m> diverges if it does not converge to a real number <m>x_0</m>.  Negating the definition of convergence, this means that there exists an <m>\epsilon>0</m> for which, regardless of your choice of <m>N \in \mathbb{N}</m> one can find an <m>n_0 &gt; N</m> for which <m>|x_n-x_0|> \epsilon</m>. </statement>
</definition>

<example><title>Divergent sequence</title>
<p workspace="5in">Define the sequeqnce <m>(x_n)</m> by <m>x_n=n</m>.  Prove that this sequence diverges.</p>
</example>

<example><title>Divergent sequence</title>
<p workspace="5in">Define the sequeqnce <m>(x_n)</m> by <m>x_n=(-1)^n</m>.  Prove that this sequence diverges.</p>
</example>


</section>
